a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes n r :: nat
assumes h0 : "n = 14"
and h1 : "r = 11"
shows  "binomial n r = 364"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Compute $\dbinom{14}{11}$. The final Answer is 364
 ### Proof
 \begin{align} \dbinom{14}{11} &= \dbinom{14}{3} \\ &= \dfrac{14!}{11!3!} \\ &= \dfrac{14\times 13\times 12}{3\times 2\times 1} \\ &= 14 \times 13 \times \dfrac{12}{3\times 2\times 1} \\ &= 14\times 13\times 2 \\
 &= \boxed{364}. \end{align}
 *)

theorem
fixes n r :: nat
assumes h0 : "n = 14"
and h1 : "r = 11"
shows  "binomial n r = 364"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
a_0.informal problem: Find the binomial coefficient for $n = 14$ and $r = 11$. The final answer is 364.
